```css cloud/cloud/rainbow/modules/rainbow/css/components/copy-to-clipboard.css
@layer components {
  [data-copy-to-clipboard-default] {
    @apply _text-grey-40 hover:_text-blue-50 _text-lg;
  }
  [data-copy-to-clipboard-check] {
    @apply _text-green-50 _text-lg _hidden;
  }
}
```


I intend to target any elemetns with the `data-copy-to-clipboard-default` attribute.

See example

```
{% macro admin_link(request, model, permission=None, extra_classes='') -%}
  {% if request.app == 'cloud' %}
    {% if request.user.is_superuser or permission and request.user.has_perm(permission) %}
      <div class="_inline-block {{ extra_classes }}">
        <button data-copy-to-clipboard
                title="Copy ID to clipboard"
                type="button"
                value="{{ model.id }}"
                class="_hidden">
          <i data-copy-to-clipboard-default
             class="fa-solid fa-copy"></i>
          <i data-copy-to-clipboard-check
             class="fa-regular fa-check"></i>
        </button>
        <a href="{{ model|admin_url }}"
           title="Edit in Django Admin"
           class="hover:_no-underline _text-red-50 hover:_text-red-70">
          <i class="fas fa-user-secret"></i>
        </a>
      </div>
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}
{%- endmacro %}
```


Your CSS selector `[data-copy-to-clipboard-default]` is correct for targeting elements with the `data-copy-to-clipboard-default` attribute. In your example, it will style the `<i>` element that has this attribute.

The CSS applies the following Tailwind utilities to elements with this attribute:
- `_text-grey-40`: Sets the text color to a grey shade
- `hover:_text-blue-50`: Changes the text color to blue on hover
- `_text-lg`: Sets the text size to large

Similarly, `[data-copy-to-clipboard-check]` targets elements with that attribute and applies green text color, large text size, and hides the element by default (`_hidden`).

This setup appears to be part of a copy-to-clipboard feature where:
1. The copy icon is shown by default in grey, turning blue on hover
2. The check icon is hidden initially and presumably shown after a successful copy operation
3. The styling is scoped within the `@layer components` directive, which is a good practice for component-specific styles in Tailwind

The markup and styling look correct for implementing this functionality.
